          "body": "Job does not respond directly to Bildad's speech in chapters 26-27. He launches immediately into his own counter-speech, beginning with sharp sarcasm: 'What a help you are to the weak! How you have saved the arm without strength!' (Job 26:2). The counter is devastating — Job takes Bildad's cosmic realities (God's power, the celestial lights, the heavenly order) and expands them far beyond what Bildad managed, while refusing to draw Bildad's conclusion. Job knows God is transcendent. He knows he is mortal and weak. But he also knows what Bildad has refused to engage: that he, Job, has done nothing to deserve what has happened to him, and that a God of true justice must reckon with that. Job's silence in response to Bildad is not acquiescence; it is contempt. When a man is covered in sores on an ash-heap and his friend delivers a six-verse lecture on cosmic ontology, the most honest response may be to refuse the frame entirely and start again from the ground."
