        "excerpt": "How then can a man be just with God? Or how can he be clean who is born of woman?",
        "body": "Verse 4 is the book of Job's central question, and Bildad is not the first friend to ask it. Eliphaz asked it in Job 4:17 ('Can mankind be just before God?') and again in Job 15:14 ('What is man that he should be pure, and he who is born of a woman that he should be righteous?'). The repetition across two friends signals that the question is not merely Bildad's private theology — it represents the friends' shared assumption. Their entire retribution framework depends on the answer being 'no human being.'\n\nThe verb tsadaq (to be just, righteous) carries legal freight. The question is not merely ethical ('can a person be morally good?') but forensic ('can a person win a legal case against God?'). Job has been demanding precisely this — a day in court (Job 13:3, 13-18; 23:3-7). Bildad's rhetorical question is designed to pre-empt the trial before it starts: the defendant's claim is inadmissible because no defendant of this species can have standing.\n\nThe parallel phrase 'born of woman' (yalad ishshah) is an idiom for human mortality — it appears in Job 14:1, 15:14, and later in the Gospels (Matthew 11:11). It does not specifically impugn the sinfulness of the birth process; it marks the creature as creaturely, as finite, as perishable. Bildad is not making a claim about original sin's transmission through birth (that is Augustine's reading of Paul, not Bildad's Hebrew argument). He is making a claim about ontological distance: the creature born into time and mortality cannot bridge the infinite qualitative gap between creaturely and divine purity.\n\nThe tragedy of verse 4 is that the right question is being used to suppress the right answer. Bildad intends the question to silence Job. The book of Job as a whole intends it to drive the reader toward a God who will justify Job (Job 42:7) and toward a gospel that answers the question: God justifies the ungodly through faith (Romans 4:5). The Mediator Job longed for in Job 9:33 — someone who could place a hand on both God and man — is Jesus Christ, 'one mediator between God and men' (1 Timothy 2:5), who was himself 'born of woman' (Galatians 4:4) and thus took the very human condition Bildad uses as disqualification and made it the instrument of reconciliation.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Tsadaq* (to be just, v.4) is the Qal imperfect of the same root as *tsaddiq* (righteous one), the term God applies to Job in 1:1 and 1:8. The irony is stark: Bildad asks 'can a man be tsadaq?' and the reader knows God has already said Job IS tsadaq. *Zakhah* (clean, pure) appears in Psalm 51:4 — 'that You may be justified [tsadaq] when You speak, and blameless [zakhah] when You judge' — David's penitential psalm uses the same two words for God's righteousness and purity that Bildad denies to man."
