        "title": "The worm and the Mediator — Bildad's climax and its canonical reversal",
        "range": "25:6",
        "excerpt": "How much less man, that maggot, and the son of man, that worm!",
        "body": "Bildad's climax in verse 6 is the most rhetorically extreme anthropological statement in the book of Job. The fortiori marker 'how much less' (aph ki) drives the argument to its floor: if celestial beings fall short, man — the weakest of all — falls infinitely shorter. The two images, rimmah (maggot, worm of decay) and tola (crimson worm, grub), are chosen with precision. Rimmah is the worm of corpses and putrefaction (Exodus 16:20; Job 7:5; Job 17:14 where Job himself uses it: 'I call the pit my father; to the worm, my mother and my sister'). Tola is the dye-worm, used in Exodus for the crimson thread of the tabernacle furnishings — an image of lowly utility.\n\nThe combination of enosh (mortal man, v.6) with rimmah, and ben adam (son of man, the image-bearer of Genesis 1:26-27) with tola, is deliberate and devastating. Bildad takes the highest human term — ben adam, the one made in God's image — and attaches to it the most debasing image available. The son of Adam, the image of God, is a worm. This is the theological low point of the friends' entire argument.\n\nThe canonical reversal is remarkable. Psalm 22:6 — the psalm of dereliction that Jesus quotes from the cross — uses precisely this language: 'I am a worm (tola) and not a man, a reproach of men and despised by the people.' The psalm's speaker endures the full weight of Bildad's verdict — worm, despised, forsaken. And then the psalm pivots (Psalm 22:24): 'For He has not despised or disdained the suffering of the afflicted one; He has not hidden His face from him but has listened to his cry for help.' The worm-language of abandonment does not end in condemnation. It ends in vindication, in the proclamation of God's righteousness to coming generations (Psalm 22:30-31). Isaiah 41:14 applies the same tola language to Israel — 'do not fear, you worm Jacob' — and immediately follows with 'I myself will help you, declares the LORD' (Isaiah 41:14). The worm is not beyond God's help; the worm is precisely the object of God's announced help.\n\nBildad stops at the worm. He does not know the rest of the psalm or the rest of the promise. His theology has a true diagnosis — human creatureliness is real, the gap between divine and human purity is real — but his prognosis is despair. The gospel's prognosis is that the one 'born of woman' (Galatians 4:4), who became the 'worm' of Psalm 22:6, endured God-forsakenness (Matthew 27:46) so that every human being who trusts Him can be declared tsadaq — just with God — on terms Bildad never imagined.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rimmah* (maggot) appears in Job 7:5; 17:14; 21:26; 24:20 — Job himself has used this word of the grave. *Tola* (worm) is the same word as the crimson dye of Exodus 25:4 and the 'worm' of Psalm 22:6. *Ben adam* (son of man) is the full image-bearer term of Genesis 1:26, also the primary self-designation of the Son of God in the Gospels (Mark 10:45; Daniel 7:13-14). Bildad applies it as a diminutive; Jesus reclaims it as a title of glory and suffering simultaneously."
